{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17657667","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17657667"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:32:41+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:32:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20589"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20589","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20589"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13466"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"93760"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13466","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13466"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20589"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76970"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"4914"},{"type":"tags","id":"12504"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"},{"type":"tags","id":"12797"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32158"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32160"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"93760","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/93760"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old man presents with severe pain in his right foot, particularly when walking. He has smoked 20 cigarettes daily for the past 15 years. Examination reveals cool extremities with diminished pulses in the right foot. A biopsy of the affected vessel is performed.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following histopathological finding is most likely to be seen?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Granulomatous inflammation with giant cells","Segmental thrombosing vasculitis","Fibrinoid necrosis with neutrophilic infiltration","Eosinophilic infiltration with extravascular granulomas","Atherosclerotic plaque with calcification"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most characteristic histopathological finding in thromboangiitis obliterans is \u003Cstrong\u003Esegmental thrombosing vasculitis \u003C/strong\u003EThis condition, also known as Buerger disease, features acute and chronic inflammation of medium and small-sized arteries (particularly the tibial and radial arteries) with occlusive thrombi. Unlike other vasculitides, the internal elastic lamina remains intact, and there is relative preservation of the vessel wall architecture.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGranulomatous inflammation with giant cells\u003C/strong\u003E is more characteristic of giant cell arteritis or granulomatosis with polyangiitis, not thromboangiitis obliterans.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFibrinoid necrosis with neutrophilic infiltration\u003C/strong\u003E is typically seen in polyarteritis nodosa and other necrotising vasculitides, but is not a feature of thromboangiitis obliterans.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEosinophilic infiltration with extravascular granulomas\u003C/strong\u003E is the hallmark of eosinophilic granulomatosis with polyangiitis (formerly Churg-Strauss syndrome), not thromboangiitis obliterans.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAtherosclerotic plaque with calcification\u003C/strong\u003E is characteristic of atherosclerotic vascular disease. Thromboangiitis obliterans is a non-atherosclerotic inflammatory condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThromboangiitis obliterans has a strong association with tobacco use and primarily affects young to middle-aged adults. The disease leads to vascular insufficiency, typically of the extremities, which can result in claudication, rest pain, and tissue necrosis. The inflammatory process can extend to adjacent veins and nerves, creating a diagnostic triad of arteritis, phlebitis, and neuritis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Thromboangiitis obliterans (Buerger disease) is a non-atherosclerotic, segmental inflammatory disease affecting small and medium-sized arteries and veins.","Thromboangiitis obliterans is strongly associated with tobacco use and primarily affects young to middle-aged adults.","The pathological hallmarks include segmental thrombosing vasculitis with preservation of the internal elastic lamina and vessel wall architecture."],"references":["Mitchell RN, Halushka MK. Blood vessels. In: Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, editors. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. p. 485\u2013525."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76970"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20589"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76970","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/76970"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-22T10:03:32+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-22T10:04:16+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13466"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"93760"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4914","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4914"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Blood vessels","synonyms":[],"